among the most productive age group in West and Central Africa stood at 1.5%, 
3.4.0%, 2.5%, and 2.1% in 1990, 2000, 2010, and 2015 respectively. This study 
examined the effect of HIV/AIDS on economic growth in West Africa with focus on 
11 countries. The augmented Solow model, rooted in the neoclassical growth 
theory, was used, which was operationalized using dynamic panel data modeling 
approach. Incidence, prevalence, number of people living with HIV/AIDS (PLWHA), 
and AIDS-related deaths were used to measure HIV/AIDS. Estimations using system 
GMM returned statistically significant results while those of first difference 
and difference GMM were not. From the outcome of system GMM analysis, a 
percentage increase in incidence, prevalence, PLWHA, and AIDS deaths 
correspondingly reduced growth significantly through their effects on life 
expectancy by 0.15%, 0.02%, 0.004%, and 0.03%. Acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome deaths and PLWHA lowered economic growth through enrolment but not 
significantly. The import of the findings is that HIV/AIDS threatens growth 
through life expectancy in West Africa. Therefore, its spread in the subregion 
should be effectively contained while proper treatment should be provided for 
all infected persons.

